<subSubSection box="[151,1223,961,983]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1223,961,983]" box="[151,1223,961,983]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,961,983]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Type taxon.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Verrill, 1867" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[283,630,961,983]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[283,496,961,983]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiothela mirabilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill, A. E." box="[501,630,961,983]" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="247 - 351" part="1" refId="ref55125" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1867) Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1, 247 - 351. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13387" title="Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species" type="journal article" year="1867">Verrill, 1867</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
originally described as 
<emphasis box="[871,1216,961,983]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Ophiothrix 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[989,1216,961,983]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mirabilis" subGenus="Ophiothela">(Ophiothela) mirabilis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1028,1664]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1028,1053]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Radial shields very large, covering most of the disc. Ventral side of arms and disc covered by skin, usually obscuring the arm plates and scales. Dorsal arm plates covered by granules. Arm spines mostly turned downward, armed with thorns or hooks (
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill, A. E." box="[605,746,1100,1125]" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="247 - 351" part="1" refId="ref55125" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1867) Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1, 247 - 351. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13387" title="Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species" type="journal article" year="1867">Verrill 1867</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1028,1664]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1135,1160]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Comments.</emphasis>
In the original description, 
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill, A. E." box="[671,829,1135,1160]" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="247 - 351" part="1" refId="ref55125" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1867) Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1, 247 - 351. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13387" title="Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species" type="journal article" year="1867">Verrill (1867)</bibRefCitation>
mentions that the adoral shields are all in contact, forming a continuous ring around the mouth. This feature was not used here for two reasons: i) the ventral side of the disc may be covered with a skin, obscuring the oral and adoral shields, making them difficult to see, and ii) some specimens did not have skin covering the ventral disc surface, exposing ventral arm plates between the adoral shields radially, contradicting the original description. This character needs revision. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[1158,1284,1280,1304]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1158,1284,1280,1304]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiothela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<emphasis box="[151,274,1316,1340]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiothrix</emphasis>
in having the arms distinctly covered with a membranous skin, dorsal surface with granules (
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill, A. E." journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="247 - 351" part="1" refId="ref55125" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1867) Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1, 247 - 351. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13387" title="Notes on the Radiata in the Museum of Yale College, with descriptions of new genera and species" type="journal article" year="1867">Verrill 1867</bibRefCitation>
), and arms more flexible in the vertical plane (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M." box="[732,863,1351,1376]" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="637 - 655" part="9" refId="ref46140" refString="Clark, A. M. (1966) Notes on the family Ophiotrichidae (Ophiuroidea). Journal of Natural History, 9, 637 - 655. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222936608651676" title="Notes on the family Ophiotrichidae (Ophiuroidea)" type="journal article" year="1966">Clark 1966</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[882,1008,1352,1376]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[882,1008,1352,1376]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiothela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was confined to Pacific waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M." journalOrPublisher="Micronesica" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="111 - 117" part="12" refId="ref46351" refString="Clark, A. M. (1976 b) Tropical epizoic echinoderms and their distribution. Micronesica, 12, 111 - 117." title="Tropical epizoic echinoderms and their distribution" type="journal article" year="1976">Clark 1976b</bibRefCitation>
), but recently introduced populations have been described in the Atlantic (
<bibRefCitation author="Hendler, G. &amp; Migotto, A. E. &amp; Ventura, C. R. R. &amp; Wilk, L." box="[1061,1284,1388,1413]" journalOrPublisher="Coral Reefs" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1005" part="31" refId="ref48630" refString="Hendler, G., Migotto, A. E., Ventura, C. R. R. &amp; Wilk, L. (2012) Epizoic Ophiothela brittle stars have invaded the Atlantic. Coral Reefs, 31, 1005. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00338 - 012 - 0936 - 6" title="Epizoic Ophiothela brittle stars have invaded the Atlantic" type="journal article" year="2012">
Hendler 
<emphasis box="[1159,1209,1388,1412]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). Its presence has changed the appearance and ecology of coral reefs as the species is often associated with gorgonians and sponges (
<bibRefCitation author="James, D. B." box="[257,395,1460,1485]" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="272 - 276" part="37" refId="ref49376" refString="James, D. B. (1995) Animal associations in echinoderms. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India, 37, 272 - 276." title="Animal associations in echinoderms" type="journal article" year="1995">James 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Goh, N. K. C. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. &amp; Chou, L. M." box="[408,590,1460,1485]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Marine Science" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="259 - 282" part="65" refId="ref47706" refString="Goh, N. K. C., Ng, P. K. L. &amp; Chou, L. M. (1999) Notes on the shallow water gorgonian-associated fauna on coral reefs in Singapore. Bulletin of Marine Science, 65, 259 - 282." title="Notes on the shallow water gorgonian-associated fauna on coral reefs in Singapore" type="journal article" year="1999">
Goh 
<emphasis box="[464,514,1460,1484]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. 1999
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hendler, G. &amp; Migotto, A. E. &amp; Ventura, C. R. R. &amp; Wilk, L." box="[603,828,1460,1485]" journalOrPublisher="Coral Reefs" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1005" part="31" refId="ref48630" refString="Hendler, G., Migotto, A. E., Ventura, C. R. R. &amp; Wilk, L. (2012) Epizoic Ophiothela brittle stars have invaded the Atlantic. Coral Reefs, 31, 1005. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00338 - 012 - 0936 - 6" title="Epizoic Ophiothela brittle stars have invaded the Atlantic" type="journal article" year="2012">
Hendler 
<emphasis box="[701,751,1460,1484]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). The implications of this association are still unclear due to the limited number of studies. One laboratory based study suggests that the coral might gain some benefit from this association through the removal of sediment build-up due brittle star movement (
<bibRefCitation author="Sneli, J." box="[1165,1291,1532,1557]" journalOrPublisher="Fauna (Oslo)" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="117 - 119" part="38" refId="ref53728" refString="Sneli, J. (1985) Paramuricea placomus in Trondheimsfjorden, Norway. Fauna (Oslo), 38, 117 - 119." title="Paramuricea placomus in Trondheimsfjorden, Norway" type="journal article" year="1985">Sneli 1985</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[1310,1436,1532,1556]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1310,1436,1532,1556]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiothela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presently includes six species (
<bibRefCitation author="Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A." box="[519,726,1567,1592]" journalOrPublisher="PLoS ONE" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="0164562" part="11" refId="ref54292" refString="Stohr, S. &amp; Martynov, A. (2016) Paedomorphosis as an Evolutionary Driving Force: Insights from Deep-Sea Brittle Stars. PLoS ONE, 11, e 0164562. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0164562" title="Paedomorphosis as an Evolutionary Driving Force: Insights from Deep-Sea Brittle Stars" type="journal article" year="2016">
Stöhr 
<emphasis box="[594,649,1568,1592]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
) with one recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1040,1108,1567,1592]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Barboza, C. A. M. &amp; Borges, M." box="[1129,1421,1567,1592]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 21" part="3447" refId="ref44247" refString="Barboza, C. A. M. &amp; Borges, M. (2012) A checklist of the extant species of ophiuroids (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Brazilian waters. Zootaxa, 3447, 1 - 21." title="A checklist of the extant species of ophiuroids (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) from Brazilian waters" type="journal article" year="2012">Barboza &amp; Borges 2012</bibRefCitation>
): 
<taxonomicName authority="Verril, 1867" authorityName="Verril" authorityYear="1867" box="[151,497,1604,1629]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="danae">
<emphasis box="[151,353,1604,1628]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ophiothela danae</emphasis>
Verril, 1867
</taxonomicName>
. However, another species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[811,946,1604,1628]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[811,946,1604,1628]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O. mirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was recorded by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hendler, G. &amp; Migotto, A. E. &amp; Ventura, C. R. R. &amp; Wilk, L." box="[1152,1388,1604,1629]" journalOrPublisher="Coral Reefs" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1005" part="31" refId="ref48630" refString="Hendler, G., Migotto, A. E., Ventura, C. R. R. &amp; Wilk, L. (2012) Epizoic Ophiothela brittle stars have invaded the Atlantic. Coral Reefs, 31, 1005. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00338 - 012 - 0936 - 6" title="Epizoic Ophiothela brittle stars have invaded the Atlantic" type="journal article" year="2012">
Hendler 
<emphasis box="[1250,1298,1604,1628]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. (2012)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Mantelatto, M. C. &amp; Vidon, L. F. &amp; Silveira, S. B. &amp; Menegola, C. &amp; Rocha, R. M. &amp; Creed, J. C." box="[151,417,1639,1664]" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity Records" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 7" part="9" refId="ref51226" refString="Mantelatto, M. C., Vidon, L. F., Silveira, S. B., Menegola, C., Rocha, R. M. &amp; Creed, J. C. (2016) Host species of the nonindigenous brittle star Ophiothela mirabilis (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea): an invasive generalist in Brazil? Marine Biodiversity Records, 9, 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 41200 - 016 - 0013 - x" title="Host species of the nonindigenous brittle star Ophiothela mirabilis (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea): an invasive generalist in Brazil?" type="journal article" year="2016">
Mantelatto 
<emphasis box="[279,328,1640,1664]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. (2016)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1867" box="[471,642,1639,1664]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiotrichidae" genus="Ophiothela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[471,498,1640,1663]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">O.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[541,642,1640,1664]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">mirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Alitto, R. A. S. &amp; Bueno, M. L. &amp; Di Domenico, M. &amp; Borges, M." box="[684,894,1639,1664]" journalOrPublisher="Check List" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 15" part="12" refId="ref43623" refString="Alitto, R. A. S., Bueno, M. L., Di Domenico, M. &amp; Borges, M. (2016) Annotated checklist of Echinoderms from Araca Bay, Southeastern Brazil. Check List, 12, 1 - 15. https: // doi. org / 10.15560 / 12.1.1836" title="Annotated checklist of Echinoderms from Araca Bay, Southeastern Brazil" type="journal article" year="2016">
Alitto 
<emphasis box="[756,806,1640,1664]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al</emphasis>
. (2016)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
